climbs.name: Universal Conflicts
climbs.fa: Roy Suggett, Gene Vallee, and Andy Ross

content.description: The crux is in my head.  I am conflicted about this route.  The first 2/3s of this trad line are three plus stars...the last third will make you ponder the truths of the universe.  So perhaps the anchor should be moved down 15 ft.?  The crack takes gear well and the liebacking is epic.  Then you turn the small roof and see sketchy rock.  So I put a bolt in here to give courage.  If you want to add a bolt here and make it an anchor...be my quest...or thrash on with your belayer well out of range (we tried to clean, pry, and scrub but the blocks look so tenuous and yet refused to budge).
content.protection: BD .4 through #1 X 2, one QD for the one bolt, and runners for the anchor composed of two bolts, a chain and a quicklink (see FA rack photo).
content.location: Just south of the Banshee Perch (a small tower on a hump of talus) on the main wall.  The crack is an obvious line.

content.description: Same start as One then head left past bolts to finish at same anchor.
content.protection: Bolts. Small/med nut or blue TCU for the finish if you want.
content.location: Left of Rain stopped Play.

content.description: Start up crack/corner until you can step right on to face. Blast up the steepening face to anchor. Brilliant climbing.
content.protection: .3 to .75, 2-#3 & 1#4 cams then bolts.
content.location: About 10 min boulder hop from the left hand end of Crag. Just left of Siouxsie Sioux.

content.description: This colorful line grows progressively difficult as well as committing the higher you climb.  The crux, as it often is in the Jungle, is at the very end. Here is also where the gear placements come.  Up to that point you were clipping bolts.  With the many and varied colored species of lichen on both your right and left as well as Bryce Canyon National Park at your back, this is an aesthetic line! The route is also a great warm up for the stiffer and fine lines to the north!
content.protection: Five quick draws gets you past the first 5 bolts and to the crux move(s).  Here you will want to have a Red C-3, BD .3 and .4.  Pull through these moves to chains with a quick link.
content.location: Just about in the middle of the Banshee Wall between the Ban Cheese Pillar and the short route known as the "One Bolt Wonder".  It is better to approach this line from the northerly descent(s) rather than come down the fixed line further south and then have to back track through some sketchy talus.

content.description: This is a great little introductory route with a serious but short talus approach. On good rock with a nice "welcome to Jungle aretes" aspect.  There are possible other lines on both sides of this one.
content.protection: The three bolts will require three QDs as well as some runners for the two bolt anchor.  A chain is here but needs a quick-link. Sorry.
content.location: Opposite the main wall and just south of the "Banshee Perch" on an up-lifted low angle outside ridge.

content.description:
A great route on the best rock the Jungle has to offer.

Crux moves in the middle lead to a sweet finish.
content.protection: Bolts.
content.location: This route is at the furthest end of the Crag. About 100ft right and around the corner from Jigsaw Feeling. Go down from the top on the fixed line or 15 min walk along the base.

content.description:
Start right up easy climbing to the ledge below the first bolt. Climb face in to the right facing corner where it gets harder the higher you go.

Great finish on steep head wall to anchor.

Almost 4 stars.
content.protection: Bolts.
content.location: This is on the main buttress 5 minutes across the talus from The Keener/Aibell. It's the middle tower of the 3 towers.

content.description: Climb past 2 bolts to the crack. Up this to the anchor, good pro, fun route.
content.protection: Bolts. Wires, 1/4 " to 2" cams.
content.location:
A few minutes right of Banshee Perch tower.

Coming from the top. Down the fixed rope in the gully, (the green slabby pillar is opposite), then right just past Universal Conflicts crack.

content.description: Most likely this short line will be used to teach or perhaps to access the anchor and top rope the  very tricky "Mopping Up Banshee Gravy". On decent rock and the view from the top of the Banshee Perch is worth the short romp.
content.protection: One QD and one BD .75 along with some runners for the two bolt anchor which has a chain and a quick-link.
content.location: On the north side of the Banshee Perch (a small tower) and just around the corner (arete) from "Mopping Up Banshee Gravy"

content.description: Start up seam to crack finish.
content.protection: Bolts. Fingers to hands cams.
content.location: Starts left of Rain stopped Play. About 100ft right of rope approach. Middle of crag.

climbs.name: My Ikran
climbs.fa: Phyllis Suggett, Andy Ross, Gene Vallee, Roy Suggett

content.description:
The easy to reach and left-sweeping moderate has been well cleaned though it's shady location will continue to give lichens a place to grow.

Beta:  The off-width crack at the top is doable with the help of a hidden finger crack within the gaping jaws.
content.protection:
BD .5 through #1 x 1 and #3 x 2.

Two bolt anchor with rings.
content.location: In the middle of the Banshee Wall area sitting on a high bench above the talus.  Car to crack = 7 minutes.  Follow cairns or walk the steep road down until you are at the approximate same elevation as the bottom of the cliff base and then cut back south across the talus.

content.description: A very dynamic and movement filled route for such a short line. You will get your money's worth here.  This is a whole lot of fun and gets you roosting atop of the Banshee Perch (a small tower) and perhaps doing a bit of crowing.  The first 4 or 5 moves gaining the SW arete and then traversing left are the sharp end of this exciting romp.
content.protection: Four QDs gets you to the chains with a quick link.
content.location: On the west side of the Banshee Perch and just south of Ban Cheese (Andy's & Gene's line) and just around the arete from "One Bolt Wonder".

content.description: A bouldery start leads to easier climbing the higher you go. Nice moves.
content.protection: Bolts then a few cams from fingers to hands.
content.location:
The route starts just right of the obvious crack that is Universal Conflicts.

Easiest way down is by fixed rope about half way along the top (5 mins from parking) or walk along bottom for 10 mins.

content.description: Starts up small crimps past the first few bolts to a good rest, then move right and finish up the same great finish as Aibell.
content.protection: Bolts.
content.location: First route you pass on the left end of the crag.

content.description: Up corner, pull a few hard moves around and over the roof. Romp up some great rock to the anchor.
content.protection: Bolts.
content.location: 30ft right of Into the Light.

climbs.name: Into the Light.
climbs.fa: Andy Ross, Gene Vallee & Roy Suggett.

content.description: A super nice gear route you can rest all the way up. Start up the corner, pull round roof then carry on up the crack to anchor.
content.protection: Wires. Cams from 1/4" to 3". Save a hand piece for the last moves.
content.location:
5 minutes from Banshee Perch, 15mins from The Keener.

Coming from the top. Down the fixed line in gully, (the green slabby pillar is opposite) then walk left (south).

content.description: A great little outing which packs some tricky moves up the arete. Would be 3 stars if it was 10ft longer. Oh well.
content.protection: Bolts
content.location: This route is a few minutes up and right from The Keener/Aibell . 20ft right of My Ikran crack.

content.description: I want to be clear here!  The start has a suspicious looking death block. Could not budge it with a crowbar and the laws of physics say its mass is TOO much to have mere mortals turn it into kinetic energy, but, it will get your attention as you pull on it! After that, pure fun on regular trad moves...until about 2/3rds of the way up. Then a quandary presents itself.  Big left reach gives your traverse a really enjoyable pull through move that made me say "wow, that was fun!"
content.protection:
One Red C3, then BD .3 through 5.0 X 1.

Two bolt-chain anchor with a quicklink.
content.location: Just to the right of "Banshee Port Wing" and left of "Solstice".

content.description: This unusual line starts with a must do lieback. For those of you who need some schooling on this technique, then the Banshee Port Wing is a fine place to start!  Because of the old school moves off the start, you would most certainly call this the crux.  Then, the more traditional trad climbing will take you to the top, IF you are into awkward transitions from one seem to another, as well as a bit of off width.  That being said, this short romp is a hoot and you will have fun doing so many different moves in such a short space.
content.protection:
BD .3 through 4.0 X 1.  If you have a 5, that will work better with less searching for a "skinny spot" to fit the 4.

Two bolt anchor with a chain and a quicklink.
content.location: This is in the west leaning curve of the wall that is just right of "Jigsaw Feeling" and right around the corner from "Solstice", at the end (southern extreme) of the Banshee Wall.

climbs.name: Banshee Holiday
climbs.fa: R. Suggett (solo) days after the cleaning, anchor setting and working out the moves on a fixed line) & Holly Hansen (In very cold and windy conditions

content.description: Unlike most Jungle lines, not at the start or the end, but dead center and the crux will most certainly work you.  Once you get into the .75 finger lock, the grind will go straight forwardly.  It is that mid-way transition that will make you wish for another holiday.
content.protection: Small cams and nuts, BD .75 X 4, #2 & #3 x 1 as well as gear for the two bolt anchor that has a chain and a quick link.
content.location: Between Aibell and My Ikran and up on a hump that is a bit loose.

content.description: Climb past 3 bolts then move right to the crack. Up the crack/face to below small roof. Pull some hard moves between rests to the anchor.
content.protection: Bolts. You can place some med/big stoppers in the crack between bolts.
content.location: This is 5 minutes from the first routes. Its on the final tower of the 3, 20ft down from Siouxsie Sioux.

content.description: Long pulls past the first bolts lead to a tricky move to the arete. Then a superb steep finish on jugs to the top.
content.protection: Bolts
content.location: Starts 20 ft right of The Keener.

content.description: Climb obvious seam to bolt two and do crux before clipping bolt 3.  Continue on to more hard climbing above.
content.protection: 6 bolts to belay
content.location: Route is located between" Into the Light" and "Jigsaw Feeling"
